<TITLE> Market slides on credit, recession fears </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW YORK, March 13 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - US stocks tumbled on Thursday as the latest signs of global credit stress rattled investors, while a surprise drop in US retail sales fueled concerns about a consumer-led recession. The decline came two days after a Fed-led move to inject cash into the market sparked stocks' biggest rally in five years. Analysts said the Fed's initiative was not enough to solve the market's problems, and risk aversion again took hold. In the latest credit market fallout, a fund affiliated with US-based buyout firm Carlyle Group, Carlyle Capital Group, said on Wednesday its lenders were likely to seize its remaining assets after it defaulted on about $16.6 billion of debt. For details, see ID:nL13503384. Shares of insurer American International Group Inc fell nearly 7 percent on concerns the world's No. 1 insurer could face larger-than-expected losses from a credit derivatives portfolio that has already led it to $11 billion in write-downs. ID:nN13149026. "This decline today has its roots in yesterday when the Street started saying that the Fed's initiative wouldn't work. And every day there's some evidence of credit stress," said Jim Paulsen, chief investment officer at Wells Capital Management in Minneapolis. The Dow Jones industrial average was down 184.39 points, or 1.52 percent, at 11,925.85. The Standard & Poor's 500 Index was down 21.34 points, or 1.63 percent, at 1,287.43. The Nasdaq Composite Index was down 31.92 points, or 1.42 percent, at 2,211.95. In another troubling sign for the economy, a government report showed retail sales tumbled in February, defying economists' forecasts for a rise. ID:nN12222686. The Fed led a coordinated effort on Tuesday with other major central banks to add liquidity to the financial system. But financial services company shares fell on Thursday, with the S&P financials group dropping 3.5 percent. A sharp drop in the dollar, soaring oil prices and US gold futures rising above $1000 per ounce added to concerns about the outlook for the consumer and inflation. The dollar dropped through 100 yen for the first time in 12 years, while oil clung close to its record high above $110 a barrel. A weaker dollar, coupled with high oil prices, makes consumer goods more expensive at a time the economy is slowing. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson issued a call for U.S. financial institutions to raise capital quickly so they can keep lending. He pledged tougher rules for the mortgage indust
